---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith('/')
  ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL
  : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Research Use Cases"
  description="Evidence-based research workflows that shaped CodeArmy: JUNO Monte Carlo tuning and CEPC FastSim DiT optimization."
>
  <section class="container page-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Research Use Cases</p>
    <h1>Real research workflows, not AI hype.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      CodeArmy's design comes from long-horizon work in particle-physics simulation and generative-model optimization. These two campaigns shaped its repo-first orchestration model.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container page-body">
    <article class="card" style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
      <h2 style="margin: 0 0 0.6rem; font-size: 1.35rem; font-weight: 700;">JUNO Monte Carlo parameter tuning</h2>
      <p>
        Monte Carlo parameter optimization is not a one-off script run. It is a multi-round campaign of hypothesis, experiment, and review. Each iteration involves candidate parameter sets, cluster job submissions, physics metric evaluation, and group-meeting reporting.
      </p>

      <div class="split-grid" style="margin-top: 1.25rem; align-items: stretch;">
        <div>
          <h3 class="mini-title">Artifacts & evidence</h3>
          <ul class="page-list">
            <li>Candidate parameter sets tied to observed physics metrics.</li>
            <li>Cluster run logs associated with the same campaign state.</li>
            <li>Phase summaries that become the basis for group decisions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Why repo-first matters</strong>
          Parameter tuning spans months of iteration. Chat logs and temporary scripts cannot sustain reproducibility. Anchoring hypotheses, code changes, experimental evidence, and review comments in the repo is what keeps long-term work from losing context.
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="card" style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
      <h2 style="margin: 0 0 0.6rem; font-size: 1.35rem; font-weight: 700;">CEPC fast-simulation DiT optimization</h2>
      <p>
        Diffusion Transformer (DiT) optimization in fast simulation involves model architecture adjustments, training pipeline changes, and speed-quality tradeoff assessments. Every experiment can affect downstream physics analysis and requires strict change control.
      </p>

      <div class="split-grid" style="margin-top: 1.25rem; align-items: stretch;">
        <div>
          <h3 class="mini-title">Artifacts & evidence</h3>
          <ul class="page-list">
            <li>Comparisons of model variants across metrics, resources, and sample quality.</li>
            <li>Review-gate records explaining why a baseline was adopted or rejected.</li>
            <li>Durable reports derived from experiment outcomes, not ephemeral chat notes.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Why repo-first matters</strong>
          Model optimization produces a large number of experimental branches. Without a structured campaign to track each variant's code, configuration, and evaluation results, the team cannot reconstruct the rationale behind decisions months later.
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
      <strong>Fact boundary</strong>
      The task shapes and artifact types on this page reflect the real usage experience of CodeArmy's designer in JUNO and CEPC FastSim projects. No unverified quantitative performance data or benchmark claims are included.
    </div>

    <div class="hero-actions">
      <a class="button" href={`${baseUrl}docs/quickstart/`}>Read Quickstart</a>
      <a class="button-secondary" href={`${baseUrl}how-it-works/`}>How It Works</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
